GitHub Copilot: ## What is the `ReShade` framework?

`ReShade` is a post-processing injector and shader framework for games and graphics software. It is not a traditional development framework like React or .NET, but a runtime tool that lets you apply custom shaders and visual effects to any application that uses DirectX, OpenGL, or Vulkan.

## How `ReShade` works

- Injects itself into the rendering pipeline of a target application.
- Captures the rendered frame just before it is displayed.
- Applies one or more shader passes to the image.
- Outputs the modified final image to the screen.

## Main components

- `ReShade64.dll` / `ReShade32.dll` – injected runtime library.
- `ReShade.ini` – configuration file with settings and hotkeys.
- `Shaders` folder – contains shader files (`.fx`) and presets.
- `ReShade.fx` – the built-in standard shader chain.
- `presets` folder – collection of effect setups users can switch between.

## Key features

- Custom post-processing effects:
  - color grading
  - bloom
  - ambient occlusion
  - depth of field
  - motion blur
  - sharpening
  - LUT-based color correction
- Shader API:
  - supports HLSL/FX shaders
  - custom shader macros and technique definitions
- Preset system:
  - users can save and load visual profiles
  - easy enable/disable per effect
- Universal compatibility:
  - works with many games and rendering engines
  - supports DirectX 9/10/11/12, OpenGL, Vulkan

## Why it is called a framework

People sometimes call `ReShade` a framework because:

- it provides a reusable shader injection layer
- it defines a plugin-like architecture for effects
- developers can build custom shaders on top of it
- it abstracts low-level graphics API details for post-processing

## Practical use cases

- enhance older games without native HDR or modern post-processing
- create cinematic or stylized visual presets
- improve clarity and detail with sharpening or ambient occlusion
- test custom shader ideas quickly
- add screen-space effects not present in the original game

## Important notes

- `ReShade` is primarily a client-side mod/overlay tool.
- It can be blocked by anti-cheat systems in multiplayer games.
- Performance cost depends on the number and complexity of shaders.
- It is widely used by modders and visual enthusiasts rather than game developers.

